metadata.name: Sedimentary Dissolution #77
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by the geological processes related to sedimentary dissolution. Dissolution is a form of weathering which contributes to the creation of new rocks. In this piece, various algorithms take on the role of dissolution, producing visual recombinations of the original "sedimentary rock".

Instructions ::

p : save a hi-res image
e : toggle erosion on and off
s : toggle structure on and off
a : toggle all effects on and off

If offset, rgb dissolution or cross-bedding is true you can toggle it on and off.
If these features are false pressing the key will have no effect.

o : toggle offset on and off
r : toggle rgb dissolution on and off
c : toggle cross-bedding on and off

There are 20 versions you can explore, all using the same features.
Use the left and right arrow to change the random seed. 
Pressing space will re-instantiate the original random seed.

metadata.name: Ailerons #91
metadata.description:
Ailerons, littering the factory floor, custom made and ready to be fitted to their respective aircraft. An accent trickles across the canvas, coloring any object in its path.

A study of light, built entirely in a 2d renderer, creating light and shadow with math and logic.

Press 's' to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Learning to Draw #42
metadata.description:
It's a collaboration between the computer and me. I tried to teach them to draw like a human artist, with all the imperfection that it means, and they tried to teach me to draw as a computer artist, with all the perfection that it means. The result is a cluster of approximative dots, jiggly lines and perfect bubbles, highlighted by colors carefully selected by them and me, after a long night of review, arguing and drinking red wine.

This is both of us, learning to draw.

PS: If any wanted or unwanted bug is found in an iteration, consider it as a blessing from the Genart Gods

Cheat codes:
* Press 1-8 to change resolution (or add &res=x to the url)
* Press s to save a PNG (or add &s=1 to the url)

metadata.name: Botanical Ghosts #39
metadata.description:
This is a work about growth, impermanence and decay. Ghostly plants and flowers grow around an invisible point, but they immediately begin to fade into the dark background and are soon replaced and covered by others. This process of accumulation and disappearance builds an ever-changing floral garland, or perhaps a funeral wreath.

The monochrome vegetation is part of a fictional flora, born out of random algorithmic combinations, and does not intend to reproduce any real species. It belongs to an “artificial nature” which, like so many worlds that the computers generate for us in movies, games, and virtual reality environments, is a convincing simulation of life, but it is not actually living. AI bots, virtual assistants and non-player characters are also representatives of the uncanny realm of the not-really-alive-but-looking-like-it, which are becoming an increasingly relevant presence in our everyday lives.

These plants and flowers speak about life as a process of incessant renovation, but also about death as the background that’s always there and makes life possible. This spectral vegetation seems to thrive precisely at the verge between both worlds.
_______________


This work is animated and will adapt to any screen size. It generates a never-ending ring of algorithmic foliage, which never repeats itself, and is different for each token. The image preview is triggered after the first five plants or flowers.
Made with p5.js

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture

metadata.name: The Beauty of Discord #73
metadata.description:
This experimental artwork is a unique blend of human and machine inputs, showcasing the potential for collaboration between the two in the creative process. The human component of the piece is evident in the deliberate composition, choice of color, and the use of painting algorithms. Meanwhile, the machine component is represented by two powerful AI technologies. The first, ChatGPT3, generated a thought-provoking poem about the galaxies and cosmos, serving as the inspiration for the piece. The second, DALL-E 2, then used this poem as a prompt to create a stunning AI image, bringing the cosmic themes to life in a realistic and captivating way.

The combination of these two AI technologies, along with the human touch in the painting algorithms and composition, creates an artwork that is truly one-of-a-kind. The final product is not only visually stunning, but it also serves as a glimpse into the future of humanity and the possibilities of AI collaboration in art. The artwork is a testament to the beauty that can result from a seemingly discordant combination of human and machine inputs, and it invites us to consider the impact of technology on the creative process and the role of the human artist in the age of AI.

Artist notes:
Press s to download high-res images.
Press a to see the AI-generated image.
Press g to switch back to the paint.

Read more on the medium website:
shorturl.at/bkqW8

metadata.name: Urban Flora #139
metadata.description:
Urban Flora is a generative artwork exploring interplay of natural and artificial forms created by Marcin Ignac / @marcinignac

http://marcinignac.com/projects/urban-flora/

The project was inspired by the 3/4/5G network infrastructure more and more present in the parks and greenery of our cities. Final Urban Flora transformed into a study of abandoned structures of a long forgotten civilisation.

The whole image is generative and/or procedural. Leaves are parametric, twigs and trees use the space colonisation algorithm, and the geometry is based on platonic solids transformed though series of operations.

Features determined at the time of minting:
- one of the platonic solids or a prism
- one of 15 geometry transformations
- a color theme
- leaves or detailed twigs
- leaf's spread and the amount of ridges

'g' / 'tree finger tap' - resolution and export
'drag' - rotate
'scroll' - zoom (on desktop)

Please note the project needs a decent GPU.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

--
With dedication to my wife.

metadata.name: Botanical Ghosts #98
metadata.description:
This is a work about growth, impermanence and decay. Ghostly plants and flowers grow around an invisible point, but they immediately begin to fade into the dark background and are soon replaced and covered by others. This process of accumulation and disappearance builds an ever-changing floral garland, or perhaps a funeral wreath.

The monochrome vegetation is part of a fictional flora, born out of random algorithmic combinations, and does not intend to reproduce any real species. It belongs to an “artificial nature” which, like so many worlds that the computers generate for us in movies, games, and virtual reality environments, is a convincing simulation of life, but it is not actually living. AI bots, virtual assistants and non-player characters are also representatives of the uncanny realm of the not-really-alive-but-looking-like-it, which are becoming an increasingly relevant presence in our everyday lives.

These plants and flowers speak about life as a process of incessant renovation, but also about death as the background that’s always there and makes life possible. This spectral vegetation seems to thrive precisely at the verge between both worlds.
_______________


This work is animated and will adapt to any screen size. It generates a never-ending ring of algorithmic foliage, which never repeats itself, and is different for each token. The image preview is triggered after the first five plants or flowers.
Made with p5.js

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
